Evola's student once told him he was in love with a girl he met at a "political event", but who was a leftist, so they were unable to be together. Evola advised him to lie to her that he was interested in Marxism and arrange a "re-educational" coffee date as an excuse to meet.

Off the start, it was clear to Evola, she was in love with the young man as much as he with her. But her ideological pretension constricted her. His acting was obvious to her, but she pretended to believe it, as now she had an excuse to let herself. Everything superficial melted.

"Everything is permitted in love!" - Evola quoted the Aryans. It worked well and the coffeeside Marxism meeting of the two led to them ending up together. But the young man told the Baron he still felt guilty he had to lie and pretend to get what he wanted. Thus Evola revealed:

Most heresies, idolatries, etc. stem from a linguistic defect. As a friend pointed out, "homosexual marriage" as a concept can exist only inside an already self-contradicting language, where most dictionary words have lost their original meaning. See Evola's "The Decay of Words".
Also as another friend said, any mention of the word "Trinity" in an English translation of Islamic texts is also most likely a mistranslation.

I carved pumpkins down in Bulgaria as a kid for Halloween as I am a cosmopolitan man, but I can never ramp my /x/ posting and paranormal phenomena analysis before the holiday, because ultimately I follow the older custom that ghost stories are best told the night of Christmas eve

As Evola explains, paganism is based on "proof". E.g. a tribesman with a "God created man from a rock" myth will take you to a big rock outside his village and show it as undeniable proof. The dancing rite over the farmer's field is proven by the lack of thunderstorm following it

When atheists still existed in 2013, a lot of them used to like making fun on "polemic" Christians, who presented Scripture as "proof" of God, usually expressed in a naive: "If God isn't real, who wrote the Bible?". Contemplating this, it strikes as a very pagan line of thinking.

In Christianity, "Faith" is centered, thus Christ says the only sign adulterous generations waiting for will get is "of the prophet Jonah". Miracles still reassure faith, but in unpious places their appearances end or turn rare. They are a fruit of faith, not a foundations of it.
